ltrating our perceptions and memories and becoming deeply rooted in thought processes that categorise and divide along culturally constructed lines. Colour exists as a cultural as well as psycho-physical phenomenon and acquires a multitude of meanings within differing historical and cultural contexts. The contributors examine how colour becomes imbued with specific symbolic and material meanings that tint our constructions of race, gender, ideal bodies, the relationship of the self to others and of the self to technology and the built environment. By highlighting the relationship of colour across media and material culture, this volume reveals the complex interplay of cultural connotations, discursive practices and socio-psychological dynamics of colour in an international context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aColorvCross-cultural studies. 0aColorxCross-cultural studies. 0aColorxPsychological aspects. 0aHuman skin color. 0aMaterial culturexElectronic books. 0aMaterial culture. 0aVisual anthropology. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies (General), History (General), Sociology.1 aBaker, Charlotte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChare, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCorris, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFigueroa, Mónica Moreno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsdick, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorrocks, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorrocks, Chris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHudek, Antony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaratheodoris, Kiki, econtributor.4ctb